# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: segment-anything
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:segment-anything/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] In digital image processing and computer vision, **image segmentation** is the process of partitioning a digital image into multiple **image segments**, also known as **image regions** or **image objects** (sets of pixels).
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The goal of segmentation is to simplify and/or change the representation of an image into something that is more meaningful and easier to analyze.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Image segmentation is typically used to locate objects and boundaries (lines, curves, etc.) in images.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] More precisely, image segmentation is the process of assigning a label to every pixel in an image such that pixels with the same label share certain characteristics.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The result of image segmentation is a set of segments that collectively cover the entire image, or a set of contours extracted from the image (see edge detection).
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Each of the pixels in a region are similar with respect to some characteristic or computed property, such as color, intensity, or texture.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Adjacent regions are significantly different with respect to the same characteristic(s).
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] When applied to a stack of images, typical in medical imaging, the resulting contours after image segmentation can be used to create 3D reconstructions with the help of geometry reconstruction algorithms like marching cubes.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Several general-purpose algorithms and techniques have been developed for image segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] To be useful, these techniques must typically be combined with a domain's specific knowledge in order to effectively solve the domain's segmentation problems.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] There are two classes of segmentation techniques.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The simplest method of image segmentation is called the thresholding method.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This method is based on a clip-level (or a threshold value) to turn a gray-scale image into a binary image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The key of this method is to select the threshold value (or values when multiple-levels are selected).
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Several popular methods are used in industry including the maximum entropy method, balanced histogram thresholding, Otsu's method (maximum variance), and k-means clustering.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Recently, methods have been developed for thresholding computed tomography (CT) images.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The key idea is that, unlike Otsu's method, the thresholds are derived from the radiographs instead of the (reconstructed) image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] New methods suggest the use of multi-dimensional, fuzzy rule-based, non-linear thresholds.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] In these approaches, the decision regarding each pixel's membership in a segment is based on multi-dimensional rules derived from fuzzy logic and evolutionary algorithms, considering factors such as image lighting, environment, and application.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Note that a common technique to improve performance for large images is to downsample the image, compute the clusters, and then reassign the values to the larger image if necessary.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The K-means algorithm is an iterative technique that is used to partition an image into *K* clusters.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] In this case, distance is the squared or absolute difference between a pixel and a cluster center.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The difference is typically based on pixel color, intensity, texture, and location, or a weighted combination of these factors.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] *K* can be selected manually, randomly, or by a heuristic.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This algorithm is guaranteed to converge, but it may not return the optimal solution.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The quality of the solution depends on the initial set of clusters and the value of *K*.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The Mean Shift algorithm is a technique that is used to partition an image into an unknown apriori number of clusters.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This has the advantage of not having to start with an initial guess of such parameter which makes it a better general solution for more diverse cases.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Motion based segmentation is a technique that relies on motion in the image to perform segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The idea is simple: look at the differences between a pair of images.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Assuming the object of interest is moving, the difference will be exactly that object.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Improving on this idea, Kenney et al. proposed interactive segmentation [2].
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] They use a robot to poke objects in order to generate the motion signal necessary for motion-based segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Interactive segmentation follows the interactive perception framework proposed by Dov Katz [3] and Oliver Brock [4].
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Another technique that is based on motion is rigid motion segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Compression based methods postulate that the optimal segmentation is the one that minimizes, over all possible segmentations, the coding length of the data.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The connection between these two concepts is that segmentation tries to find patterns in an image and any regularity in the image can be used to compress it.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The method describes each segment by its texture and boundary shape.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Texture is encoded by lossy compression in a way similar to minimum description length (MDL) principle, but here the length of the data given the model is approximated by the number of samples times the entropy of the model.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The texture in each region is modeled by a multivariate normal distribution whose entropy has a closed form expression.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] An interesting property of this model is that the estimated entropy bounds the true entropy of the data from above.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This is because among all distributions with a given mean and covariance, normal distribution has the largest entropy.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Thus, the true coding length cannot be more than what the algorithm tries to minimize.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] For any given segmentation of an image, this scheme yields the number of bits required to encode that image based on the given segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Thus, among all possible segmentations of an image, the goal is to find the segmentation which produces the shortest coding length.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This can be achieved by a simple agglomerative clustering method.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The distortion in the lossy compression determines the coarseness of the segmentation and its optimal value may differ for each image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This parameter can be estimated heuristically from the contrast of textures in an image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] For example, when the textures in an image are similar, such as in camouflage images, stronger sensitivity and thus lower quantization is required.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Histogram-based methods are very efficient compared to other image segmentation methods because they typically require only one pass through the pixels.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] In this technique, a histogram is computed from all of the pixels in the image, and the peaks and valleys in the histogram are used to locate the clusters in the image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Color or intensity can be used as the measure.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] A refinement of this technique is to recursively apply the histogram-seeking method to clusters in the image in order to divide them into smaller clusters.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This operation is repeated with smaller and smaller clusters until no more clusters are formed.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] One disadvantage of the histogram-seeking method is that it may be difficult to identify significant peaks and valleys in the image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Histogram-based approaches can also be quickly adapted to apply to multiple frames, while maintaining their single pass efficiency.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The histogram can be done in multiple fashions when multiple frames are considered.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The same approach that is taken with one frame can be applied to multiple, and after the results are merged, peaks and valleys that were previously difficult to identify are more likely to be distinguishable.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The histogram can also be applied on a per-pixel basis where the resulting information is used to determine the most frequent color for the pixel location.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This approach segments based on active objects and a static environment, resulting in a different type of segmentation useful in video tracking.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Edge detection is a well-developed field on its own within image processing.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Region boundaries and edges are closely related, since there is often a sharp adjustment in intensity at the region boundaries.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Edge detection techniques have therefore been used as the base of another segmentation technique.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The edges identified by edge detection are often disconnected.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] To segment an object from an image however, one needs closed region boundaries.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The desired edges are the boundaries between such objects or spatial-taxons.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Spatial-taxons are information granules, consisting of a crisp pixel region, stationed at abstraction levels within a hierarchical nested scene architecture.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] They are similar to the Gestalt psychological designation of figure-ground, but are extended to include foreground, object groups, objects and salient object parts.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Edge detection methods can be applied to the spatial-taxon region, in the same manner they would be applied to a silhouette.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Segmentation methods can also be applied to edges obtained from edge detectors.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The detection of isolated points in an image is a fundamental part of image segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This process primarily depends on the second derivative, indicating the use of the Laplacian operator.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The Laplacian operator is employed such that the partial derivatives are derived from a specific equation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This mathematical expression can be implemented by convolving with an appropriate mask.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] If we extend this equation to three dimensions (x,y,z), the intensity at each pixel location around a central pixel at (x, y, z) is replaced by their corresponding values.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This equation becomes particularly useful when we assume that all pixels have unit spacing along each axis.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] A sphere mask has been developed for use with three-dimensional datasets.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The sphere mask is designed to use only integer arithmetic during calculations, thereby eliminating the need for floating-point hardware or software.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] When applying these concepts to actual images represented as arrays of numbers, we need to consider what happens when we reach an edge or border region.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This above equation is used to determine whether a point in the image is an isolated point based on the response magnitude $|R(x,y)|$ and a threshold value T .
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] If the response magnitude is greater than or equal to the threshold, the function returns 1, indicating the presence of an isolated point; otherwise, it returns 0.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This helps in the effective detection and segmentation of isolated points in the image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The detection of isolated points has significant applications in various fields, including X-ray image processing.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] For instance, an original X-ray image of a turbine blade can be examined pixel-by-pixel to detect porosity in the upper-right quadrant of the blade.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The result of applying an edge detector's response to this X-ray image can be approximated.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This demonstrates the segmentation of isolated points in an image with the aid of single-pixel probes.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This method is a combination of three characteristics of the image: partition of the image based on histogram analysis is checked by high compactness of the clusters (objects), and high gradients of their borders.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] For that purpose two spaces have to be introduced: one space is the one-dimensional histogram of brightness *H* = *H*(*B*); the second space is the dual 3-dimensional space of the original image itself *B* = *B*(*x*, *y*).
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The first space allows to measure how compactly the brightness of the image is distributed by calculating a minimal clustering kmin.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The bitmap *b* is an object in dual space.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] On that bitmap a measure has to be defined reflecting how compact distributed black (or white) pixels are.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] So, the goal is to find objects with good borders.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] For all *T* the measure *M*DC = *G*/(*k* × *L*) has to be calculated (where *k* is difference in brightness between the object and the background, *L* is length of all borders, and *G* is mean gradient on the borders).
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Maximum of MDC defines the segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Region-growing methods rely mainly on the assumption that the neighboring pixels within one region have similar values.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The common procedure is to compare one pixel with its neighbors.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] If a similarity criterion is satisfied, the pixel can be set to belong to the same cluster as one or more of its neighbors.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The selection of the similarity criterion is significant and the results are influenced by noise in all instances.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The method of Statistical Region Merging (SRM) starts by building the graph of pixels using 4-connectedness with edges weighted by the absolute value of the intensity difference.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Initially each pixel forms a single pixel region.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] SRM then sorts those edges in a priority queue and decides whether or not to merge the current regions belonging to the edge pixels using a statistical predicate.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] One region-growing method is the seeded region growing method.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This method takes a set of seeds as input along with the image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The seeds mark each of the objects to be segmented.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The regions are iteratively grown by comparison of all unallocated neighboring pixels to the regions.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The difference between a pixel's intensity value and the region's mean, $\delta$ , is used as a measure of similarity.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The pixel with the smallest difference measured in this way is assigned to the respective region.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This process continues until all pixels are assigned to a region.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Because seeded region growing requires seeds as additional input, the segmentation results are dependent on the choice of seeds, and noise in the image can cause the seeds to be poorly placed.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Another region-growing method is the unseeded region growing method.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] It is a modified algorithm that does not require explicit seeds.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] It starts with a single region $A_{1}$ —the pixel chosen here does not markedly influence the final segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] At each iteration it considers the neighboring pixels in the same way as seeded region growing.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] It differs from seeded region growing in that if the minimum $\delta$ is less than a predefined threshold T then it is added to the respective region $A_{j}$ .
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] If not, then the pixel is considered different from all current regions $A_{i}$ and a new region $A_{n+1}$ is created with this pixel.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] One variant of this technique, proposed by Haralick and Shapiro (1985), is based on pixel intensities.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The mean and scatter of the region and the intensity of the candidate pixel are used to compute a test statistic.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] If the test statistic is sufficiently small, the pixel is added to the region, and the region's mean and scatter are recomputed.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Otherwise, the pixel is rejected, and is used to form a new region.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] A special region-growing method is called $\lambda$ -connected segmentation (see also lambda-connectedness).
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] It is based on pixel intensities and neighborhood-linking paths.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] A degree of connectivity (connectedness) is calculated based on a path that is formed by pixels.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] For a certain value of $\lambda$ , two pixels are called $\lambda$ -connected if there is a path linking those two pixels and the connectedness of this path is at least $\lambda$ . $\lambda$ -connectedness is an equivalence relation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Split-and-merge segmentation is based on a quadtree partition of an image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] It is sometimes called quadtree segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This method starts at the root of the tree that represents the whole image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] If it is found non-uniform (not homogeneous), then it is split into four child squares (the splitting process), and so on.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] If, in contrast, four child squares are homogeneous, they are merged as several connected components (the merging process).
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The node in the tree is a segmented node.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This process continues recursively until no further splits or merges are possible.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] When a special data structure is involved in the implementation of the algorithm of the method, its time complexity can reach $O(n\log n)$ , an optimal algorithm of the method.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Using a partial differential equation (PDE)-based method and solving the PDE equation by a numerical scheme, one can segment the image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Curve propagation is a popular technique in this category, with numerous applications to object extraction, object tracking, stereo reconstruction, etc.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The central idea is to evolve an initial curve towards the lowest potential of a cost function, where its definition reflects the task to be addressed.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] As for most inverse problems, the minimization of the cost functional is non-trivial and imposes certain smoothness constraints on the solution, which in the present case can be expressed as geometrical constraints on the evolving curve.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Lagrangian techniques are based on parameterizing the contour according to some sampling strategy and then evolving each element according to image and internal terms.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Nowadays, efficient "discretized" formulations have been developed to address these limitations while maintaining high efficiency.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] In both cases, energy minimization is generally conducted using a steepest-gradient descent, whereby derivatives are computed using, e.g., finite differences.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The level-set method was initially proposed to track moving interfaces by Dervieux and Thomasset in 1979 and 1981 and was later reinvented by Osher and Sethian in 1988.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This has spread across various imaging domains in the late 1990s.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] It can be used to efficiently address the problem of curve/surface/etc. propagation in an implicit manner.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The central idea is to represent the evolving contour using a signed function whose zero corresponds to the actual contour.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Then, according to the motion equation of the contour, one can easily derive a similar flow for the implicit surface that when applied to the zero level will reflect the propagation of the contour.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The level-set method affords numerous advantages: it is implicit, is parameter-free, provides a direct way to estimate the geometric properties of the evolving structure, allows for change of topology, and is intrinsic.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] It can be used to define an optimization framework, as proposed by Zhao, Merriman and Osher in 1996.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] One can conclude that it is a very convenient framework for addressing numerous applications of computer vision and medical image analysis.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Research into various level-set data structures has led to very efficient implementations of this method.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The fast marching method has been used in image segmentation, and this model has been improved (permitting both positive and negative propagation speeds) in an approach called the generalized fast marching method.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The goal of variational methods is to find a segmentation which is optimal with respect to a specific energy functional.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The functionals consist of a data fitting term and a regularizing terms.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] A minimizer $u^{*}$ is a piecewise constant image which has an optimal tradeoff between the squared L2 distance to the given image f and the total length of its jump set.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The jump set of $u^{*}$ defines a segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The relative weight of the energies is tuned by the parameter $\gamma >0$ .
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The binary variant of the Potts model, i.e., if the range of u is restricted to two values, is often called Chan-Vese model.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The functional value is the sum of the total length of the segmentation curve K , the smoothness of the approximation u , and its distance to the original image f .
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The weight of the smoothness penalty is adjusted by $\mu >0$ .
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The Potts model is often called piecewise constant Mumford-Shah model as it can be seen as the degenerate case $\mu \to \infty$ .
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The optimization problems are known to be NP-hard in general but near-minimizing strategies work well in practice.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Classical algorithms are graduated non-convexity and Ambrosio-Tortorelli approximation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Graph partitioning methods are an effective tools for image segmentation since they model the impact of pixel neighborhoods on a given cluster of pixels or pixel, under the assumption of homogeneity in images.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] In these methods, the image is modeled as a weighted, undirected graph.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Usually a pixel or a group of pixels are associated with nodes and edge weights define the (dis)similarity between the neighborhood pixels.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The graph (image) is then partitioned according to a criterion designed to model "good" clusters.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Each partition of the nodes (pixels) output from these algorithms are considered an object segment in the image; see Segmentation-based object categorization.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Some popular algorithms of this category are normalized cuts, random walker, minimum cut, isoperimetric partitioning, minimum spanning tree-based segmentation, and segmentation-based object categorization.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The application of Markov random fields (MRF) for images was suggested in early 1984 by Geman and Geman.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Their strong mathematical foundation and ability to provide a global optimum even when defined on local features proved to be the foundation for novel research in the domain of image analysis, de-noising and segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] MRFs are completely characterized by their prior probability distributions, marginal probability distributions, cliques, smoothing constraint as well as criterion for updating values.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The criterion for image segmentation using MRFs is restated as finding the labelling scheme which has maximum probability for a given set of features.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The broad categories of image segmentation using MRFs are supervised and unsupervised segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] In terms of image segmentation, the function that MRFs seek to maximize is the probability of identifying a labelling scheme given a particular set of features are detected in the image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This is a restatement of the maximum a posteriori estimation method.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] 3. where *fi* ∈ Σ is the set containing features extracted for pixel i and define an initial set of clusters.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Using the training data compute the mean (*μ**ℓ**i*) and variance (σ*ℓ**i*) for each label.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Compute the marginal distribution for the given labeling scheme *P*(*fi* | *ℓ**i*) using Bayes' theorem and the class statistics calculated earlier.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Calculate the probability of each class label given the neighborhood defined previously.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Clique potentials are used to model the social impact in labeling.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Iterate over new prior probabilities and redefine clusters such that these probabilities are maximized.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] This is done using a variety of optimization algorithms described below.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Stop when probability is maximized and labeling scheme does not change.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The calculations can be implemented in log likelihood terms as well.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Each optimization algorithm is an adaptation of models from a variety of fields and they are set apart by their unique cost functions.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The common trait of cost functions is to penalize change in pixel value as well as difference in pixel label when compared to labels of neighboring pixels.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] where α is the penalty for change in pixel label and β is the penalty for difference in label between neighboring pixels and chosen pixel.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Here $N(i)$ is neighborhood of pixel i and δ is the Kronecker delta function.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] A major issue with ICM is that, similar to gradient descent, it has a tendency to rest over local maxima and thus not obtain a globally optimal labeling scheme.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Derived as an analogue of annealing in metallurgy, simulated annealing (SA) uses change in pixel label over iterations and estimates the difference in energy of each newly formed graph to the initial data.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] the algorithm selects the newly formed graph.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Simulated annealing requires the input of temperature schedules which directly affects the speed of convergence of the system, as well as energy threshold for minimization to occur.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] A range of other methods exist for solving simple as well as higher order MRFs.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] They include Maximization of Posterior Marginal, Multi-scale MAP estimation, Multiple Resolution segmentation and more.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Apart from likelihood estimates, graph-cut using maximum flow and other highly constrained graph based methods exist for solving MRFs.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The expectation–maximization algorithm is utilized to iteratively estimate the a posterior probabilities and distributions of labeling when no training data is available and no estimate of segmentation model can be formed.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] E step: Estimate class statistics based on the random segmentation model defined.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Using these, compute the conditional probability of belonging to a label given the feature set is calculated using naive Bayes' theorem.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Here $\lambda \in \Lambda$ , the set of all possible labels.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] M step: The established relevance of a given feature set to a labeling scheme is now used to compute the a priori estimate of a given label in the second part of the algorithm.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Since the actual number of total labels is unknown (from a training data set), a hidden estimate of the number of labels given by the user is utilized in computations.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] where $\Omega$ is the set of all possible features.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Approximate MAP estimates are computationally expensive to calculate.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Extension to multi-class labeling degrades performance and increases storage required.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Reliable estimation of parameters for EM is required for global optima to be achieved.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Based on method of optimization, segmentation may cluster to local minima.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The watershed transformation considers the gradient magnitude of an image as a topographic surface.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Pixels having the highest gradient magnitude intensities (GMIs) correspond to watershed lines, which represent the region boundaries.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Water placed on any pixel enclosed by a common watershed line flows downhill to a common local intensity minimum (LIM).
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Pixels draining to a common minimum form a catch basin, which represents a segment.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The central assumption of model-based approaches is that the structures of interest have a tendency towards a particular shape.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Therefore, one can seek a probabilistic model that characterizes the shape and its variation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] When segmenting an image, constraints can be imposed using this model as a prior.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Such a task may involve (i) registration of the training examples to a common pose, (ii) probabilistic representation of the variation of the registered samples, and (iii) statistical inference between the model and the image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Other important methods in the literature for model-based segmentation include active shape models and active appearance models.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Image segmentations are computed at multiple scales in scale space and sometimes propagated from coarse to fine scales; see scale-space segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Segmentation criteria can be arbitrarily complex and may take into account global as well as local criteria.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] A common requirement is that each region must be connected in some sense.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Witkin's seminal work in scale space included the notion that a one-dimensional signal could be unambiguously segmented into regions, with one scale parameter controlling the scale of segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] A key observation is that the zero-crossings of the second derivatives (minima and maxima of the first derivative or slope) of multi-scale-smoothed versions of a signal form a nesting tree, which defines hierarchical relations between segments at different scales.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Specifically, slope extrema at coarse scales can be traced back to corresponding features at fine scales.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] When a slope maximum and slope minimum annihilate each other at a larger scale, the three segments that they separated merge into one segment, thus defining the hierarchy of segments.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] There have been numerous research works in this area, out of which a few have now reached a state where they can be applied either with interactive manual intervention (usually with application to medical imaging) or fully automatically.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The following is a brief overview of some of the main research ideas that current approaches are based upon.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The nesting structure that Witkin described is, however, specific for one-dimensional signals and does not trivially transfer to higher-dimensional images.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Nevertheless, this general idea has inspired several other authors to investigate coarse-to-fine schemes for image segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Koenderink proposed to study how iso-intensity contours evolve over scales and this approach was investigated in more detail by Lifshitz and Pizer.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Unfortunately, however, the intensity of image features changes over scales, which implies that it is hard to trace coarse-scale image features to finer scales using iso-intensity information.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Bergholm proposed to detect edges at coarse scales in scale-space and then trace them back to finer scales with manual choice of both the coarse detection scale and the fine localization scale.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Gauch and Pizer studied the complementary problem of ridges and valleys at multiple scales and developed a tool for interactive image segmentation based on multi-scale watersheds.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The use of multi-scale watershed with application to the gradient map has also been investigated by Olsen and Nielsen and been carried over to clinical use by Dam.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Vincken et al. proposed a hyperstack for defining probabilistic relations between image structures at different scales.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The use of stable image structures over scales has been furthered by Ahuja and his co-workers into a fully automated system.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] A fully automatic brain segmentation algorithm based on closely related ideas of multi-scale watersheds has been presented by Undeman and Lindeberg and been extensively tested in brain databases.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] These ideas for multi-scale image segmentation by linking image structures over scales have also been picked up by Florack and Kuijper.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Bijaoui and Rué associate structures detected in scale-space above a minimum noise threshold into an object tree which spans multiple scales and corresponds to a kind of feature in the original signal.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Extracted features are accurately reconstructed using an iterative conjugate gradient matrix method.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] In one kind of segmentation, the user outlines the region of interest with the mouse clicks and algorithms are applied so that the path that best fits the edge of the image is shown.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Techniques like SIOX, Livewire, Intelligent Scissors or IT-SNAPS are used in this kind of segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] In an alternative kind of semi-automatic segmentation, the algorithms return a spatial-taxon (i.e. foreground, object-group, object or object-part) selected by the user or designated via prior probabilities.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Most of the aforementioned segmentation methods are based only on color information of pixels in the image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Humans use much more knowledge when performing image segmentation, but implementing this knowledge would cost considerable human engineering and computational time, and would require a huge domain knowledge database which does not currently exist.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Trainable segmentation methods, such as neural network segmentation, overcome these issues by modeling the domain knowledge from a dataset of labeled pixels.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] An image segmentation neural network can process small areas of an image to extract simple features such as edges.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Another neural network, or any decision-making mechanism, can then combine these features to label the areas of an image accordingly.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] A type of network designed this way is the Kohonen map.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Pulse-coupled neural networks (PCNNs) are neural models proposed by modeling a cat's visual cortex and developed for high-performance biomimetic image processing.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] In 1989, Reinhard Eckhorn introduced a neural model to emulate the mechanism of a cat's visual cortex.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The Eckhorn model provided a simple and effective tool for studying the visual cortex of small mammals, and was soon recognized as having significant application potential in image processing.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] In 1994, the Eckhorn model was adapted to be an image processing algorithm by John L.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Johnson, who termed this algorithm Pulse-Coupled Neural Network.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Over the past decade, PCNNs have been utilized for a variety of image processing applications, including: image segmentation, feature generation, face extraction, motion detection, region growing, noise reduction, and so on.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] A PCNN is a two-dimensional neural network.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Each neuron in the network corresponds to one pixel in an input image, receiving its corresponding pixel's color information (e.g. intensity) as an external stimulus.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Each neuron also connects with its neighboring neurons, receiving local stimuli from them.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The external and local stimuli are combined in an internal activation system, which accumulates the stimuli until it exceeds a dynamic threshold, resulting in a pulse output.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Through iterative computation, PCNN neurons produce temporal series of pulse outputs.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The temporal series of pulse outputs contain information of input images and can be utilized for various image processing applications, such as image segmentation and feature generation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Compared with conventional image processing means, PCNNs have several significant merits, including robustness against noise, independence of geometric variations in input patterns, capability of bridging minor intensity variations in input patterns, etc.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] In 2015, convolutional neural networks reached state of the art in semantic segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] U-Net is an architecture which takes as input an image and outputs a label for each pixel.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] U-Net initially was developed to detect cell boundaries in biomedical images.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] U-Net follows classical autoencoder architecture, as such it contains two sub-structures.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The encoder structure follows the traditional stack of convolutional and max pooling layers to increase the receptive field as it goes through the layers.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] It is used to capture the context in the image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The decoder structure utilizes transposed convolution layers for upsampling so that the end dimensions are close to that of the input image.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Skip connections are placed between convolution and transposed convolution layers of the same shape in order to preserve details that would have been lost otherwise.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Related images such as a photo album or a sequence of video frames often contain semantically similar objects and scenes, therefore it is often beneficial to exploit such correlations.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] The task of simultaneously segmenting scenes from related images or video frames is termed co-segmentation, which is typically used in human action localization.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Unlike conventional bounding box-based object detection, human action localization methods provide finer-grained results, typically per-image segmentation masks delineating the human object of interest and its action category (e.g., *Segment-Tube*).
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] Techniques such as dynamic Markov Networks, CNN and LSTM are often employed to exploit the inter-frame correlations.
[src:segment-anything/image-segmentation] There are many other methods of segmentation like multispectral segmentation or connectivity-based segmentation based on DTI images.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] In computer science, a **mask** or **bitmask** is data that is used for bitwise operations, particularly in a bit field.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Using a mask, multiple bits in a byte, nibble, word, etc. can be set either on or off, or inverted from on to off (or vice versa) in a single bitwise operation.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] An additional use of masking involves predication in vector processing, where the bitmask is used to select which element operations in the vector are to be executed (mask bit is enabled) and which are not (mask bit is clear).
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] To turn certain bits on, the bitwise `OR` operation can be used, following the principle that for an individual bit **Y**, `Y OR 1 = 1` and `Y OR 0 = Y`.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Therefore, to make sure a bit is on, `OR` can be used with a `1`.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] To leave a bit unchanged, `OR` is used with a `0`.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Example: Masking *on* the higher nibble (bits 4, 5, 6, 7) while leaving the lower nibble (bits 0, 1, 2, 3) unchanged.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] More often in practice, bits are "masked *off*" (or masked to `0`) than "masked *on*" (or masked to `1`).
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] When a bit is `AND`ed with a 0, the result is always 0, i.e.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Example: Masking *off* the higher nibble (bits 4, 5, 6, 7) while leaving the lower nibble (bits 0, 1, 2, 3) unchanged.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] It is possible to use bitmasks to easily check the state of individual bits regardless of the other bits.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] To do this, turning off all the other bits using the bitwise `AND` is done as discussed above and the value is compared with `0`.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] If it is equal to `0`, then the bit was off, but if the value is any other value, then the bit was on.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] What makes this convenient is that it is not necessary to figure out what the value actually is, just that it is not `0`.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] So far the article has covered how to turn bits on and turn bits off, but not both at once.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Sometimes it does not really matter what the value is, but it must be made the opposite of what it currently is.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] This can be achieved using the `XOR` (exclusive or) operation.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] `XOR` returns `1` if and only if an odd number of bits are `1`.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Therefore, if two corresponding bits are `1`, the result will be a `0`, but if only one of them is `1`, the result will be `1`.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Therefore inversion of the values of bits is done by `XOR`ing them with a `1`.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] If the original bit was `1`, it returns `1 XOR 1 = 0`.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] If the original bit was `0` it returns `0 XOR 1 = 1`.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Also note that `XOR` masking is bit-safe, meaning that it will not affect unmasked bits because `Y XOR 0 = Y`, just like an `OR`.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Sometimes selected bits must be copied without altering other bits in a register or storage.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] For this example, *bitmask* has *0* where the *destination* bits remain, and *1* where they are replaced by *source* bits.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] In programming languages such as C, bit fields are a useful way to pass a set of named Boolean arguments to a function.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] For example, in the graphics API OpenGL, there is a command, `glClear()` which clears the screen or other buffers.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] It can clear up to four buffers (the color, depth, accumulation, and stencil buffers), so the API authors could have had it take four arguments.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Internally, a function taking a bitfield like this can use binary `and` to extract the individual bits.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] The advantage to this approach is that function argument overhead is decreased.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Since the minimum datum size is one byte, separating the options into separate arguments would be wasting seven bits per argument and would occupy more stack space.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Instead, functions typically accept one or more 32-bit integers, with up to 32 option bits in each.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] While elegant, in the simplest implementation this solution is not type-safe.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] A `GLbitfield` is simply defined to be an `unsigned int`, so the compiler would allow a meaningless call to `glClear(42)` or even `glClear(GL_POINTS)`.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] In C++ an alternative would be to create a class to encapsulate the set of arguments that glClear could accept and could be cleanly encapsulated in a library.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Masks are used with IP addresses in IP ACLs (Access Control Lists) to specify what should be permitted and denied.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] To configure IP addresses on interfaces, masks start with 255 and have the large values on the left side: for example, IP address *203.0.113.129* with a *255.255.255.224* mask.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Masks for IP ACLs are the reverse: for example, mask *0.0.0.255*.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] This is sometimes called an inverse mask or a wildcard mask.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] When the value of the mask is broken down into binary (0s and 1s), the results determine which address bits are to be considered in processing the traffic.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] A *0*-bit indicates that the address bit must be considered (exact match); a *1*-bit in the mask is ignored.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Based on the binary mask, it can be seen that the first three sets (octets) must match the given binary network address exactly (`11000000.00000000.00000010`).
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] The last set of numbers are ignored by the mask.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Thus, all traffic that begins with "`*192.0.2.*`" are matched.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Subtracting the normal mask from `*255.255.255.255*` determines the ACL inverse mask.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] In computer graphics, when a given image is intended to be placed over a background, the transparent areas can be specified through a binary mask.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] In the sample at right, black pixels have the all-zero bits and white pixels have the all-one bits.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] At run time, to put the image on the screen over the background, the program first masks the screen pixel's bits with the image mask at the desired coordinates using the bitwise AND operation.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] This preserves the background pixels of the transparent areas while resets with zeros the bits of the pixels which will be obscured by the overlapped image.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Then, the program renders the image pixel's bits by combining them with the background pixel's bits using the bitwise OR operation.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] This way, the image pixels are appropriately placed while keeping the background surrounding pixels preserved.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] The result is a perfect compound of the image over the background.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] This technique is used for painting pointing device cursors, in typical 2-D videogames for characters, bullets and so on (the sprites), for GUI icons, and for video titling and other image mixing applications.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] Although related (due to being used for the same purposes), transparent colors and alpha channels are techniques which do not involve the image pixel mixage by binary masking.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] To create a hashing function for a hash table, often a function is used that has a large domain.
[src:segment-anything/mask-computing] To create an index from the output of the function, a modulo can be taken to reduce the size of the domain to match the size of the array; however, it is often faster on many processors to restrict the size of the hash table to powers of two sizes and use a bitmask instead.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] It is widely used in computer vision tasks such as image annotation, vehicle counting, activity recognition, face detection, face recognition, video object co-segmentation.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] It is also used in tracking objects, for example tracking a ball during a football match, tracking movement of a cricket bat, or tracking a person in a video.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] Often, the test images are sampled from a different data distribution, making the object detection task significantly more difficult.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] To address the challenges caused by the domain gap between training and test data, many unsupervised domain adaptation approaches have been proposed.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] A simple and straightforward solution for reducing the domain gap is to apply an image-to-image translation approach, such as cycle-GAN.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] Among other uses, cross-domain object detection is applied in autonomous driving, where models can be trained on a vast amount of video game scenes, since the labels can be generated without manual labor.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] Every object class has its own special features that help in classifying the class – for example all circles are round.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] Object class detection uses these special features.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] For example, when looking for circles, objects that are at a particular distance from a point (i.e. the center) are sought.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] Similarly, when looking for squares, objects that are perpendicular at corners and have equal side lengths are needed.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] A similar approach is used for face identification where eyes, nose, and lips can be found and features like skin color and distance between eyes can be found.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] For object localization, true positive is often measured by the thresholded intersection over union.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] For example, if there is a traffic sign in the image, with a bounding box drawn by a human ("ground truth label"), then a neural network has detected the traffic sign (a **true positive**) at 0.5 threshold if it has drawn a bounding box whose IoU with the ground truth is above 0.5.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] Otherwise, the bounding box is a **false positive**.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] If there is only a single ground truth bounding box, but multiple predictions, then the IoU of each prediction is calculated.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] The prediction with the highest IoU is a true positive if it is above threshold, else it is a false positive.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] All other predicted bounding boxes are false positives.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] If there is no prediction with an IoU above the threshold, then the ground truth label has a **false negative**.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] For simultaneous object localization and classification, a true positive is one where the class label is correct, and the bounding box has an IoU exceeding the threshold.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] Simultaneous object localization and classification is benchmarked by the **mean average precision** (mAP).
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] The average precision (AP) of the network for a class of objects is the area under the precision-recall curve as the confidence threshold is varied.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] The mAP is the average of AP over all classes.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] Methods for object detection generally fall into either neural network-based or non-neural approaches.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] For non-neural approaches, it becomes necessary to first define features using one of the methods below, then using a technique such as support vector machine (SVM) to do the classification.
[src:segment-anything/object-detection] On the other hand, neural techniques are able to do end-to-end object detection without specifically defining features, and are typically based on convolutional neural networks (CNN).
[src:segment-anything/semantic-segmentation] Improving on this idea, Kenney et al. proposed interactive segmentation .
[src:segment-anything/semantic-segmentation] Interactive segmentation follows the interactive perception framework proposed by Dov Katz and Oliver Brock .
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] A **vision transformer** (**ViT**) is a transformer designed for computer vision.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] A ViT decomposes an input image into a series of patches (rather than text into tokens), serializes each patch into a vector, and maps it to a smaller dimension with a single matrix multiplication.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] These vector embeddings are then processed by a transformer encoder as if they were token embeddings.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] ViTs were designed as alternatives to convolutional neural networks (CNNs) in computer vision applications.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] They have different inductive biases, training stability, and data efficiency.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Compared to CNNs, ViTs are less data efficient, but have higher capacity.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Some of the largest modern computer vision models are ViTs, such as one with 22B parameters.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Subsequent to its publication, many variants were proposed, with hybrid architectures with both features of ViTs and CNNs.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] ViTs have found application in image recognition, image segmentation, weather prediction, and autonomous driving.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Transformers were introduced in *Attention Is All You Need* (2017), and have found widespread use in natural language processing.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] A 2019 paper applied ideas from the Transformer to computer vision.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Specifically, they started with a ResNet, a standard convolutional neural network used for computer vision, and replaced all convolutional kernels by the self-attention mechanism found in a Transformer.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] However, it is not a Vision Transformer.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] In 2020, an encoder-only transformer was adapted for computer vision, yielding the ViT, which reached state of the art in image classification, overcoming the previous dominance of CNN.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The masked autoencoder (2022) extended ViT to work with unsupervised training.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The vision transformer and the masked autoencoder, in turn, stimulated new developments in convolutional neural networks.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Subsequently, there was cross-fertilization between the previous CNN approach and the ViT approach.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] In 2021, some important variants of the Vision Transformers were proposed.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] These variants are mainly intended to be more efficient, more accurate or better suited to a specific domain.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Two studies improved efficiency and robustness of ViT by adding a CNN as a preprocessor.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The Swin Transformer achieved state-of-the-art results on some object detection datasets such as COCO, by using convolution-like sliding windows of attention mechanism, and the pyramid process in classical computer vision.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The basic architecture, used by the original 2020 paper, is as follows.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] In summary, it is a BERT-like encoder-only Transformer.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The input image is of type $\mathbb {R} ^{H\times W\times C}$ , where $H,W,C$ are height, width, channel (RGB).
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] It is then split into square-shaped patches of type $\mathbb {R} ^{P\times P\times C}$ .
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] For each patch, the patch is pushed through a linear operator, to obtain a vector ("patch embedding").
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The position of the patch is also transformed into a vector by "position encoding" (the paper tried no embedding, 1D embedding, 2D embedding, and relative embedding: 1D was adopted).
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The two vectors are added, then pushed through several Transformer encoders.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The attention mechanism in a ViT repeatedly transforms representation vectors of image patches, incorporating more and more semantic relations between image patches in an image.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] This is analogous to how in natural language processing, as representation vectors flow through a transformer, they incorporate more and more semantic relations between words, from syntax to semantics.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The above architecture turns an image into a sequence of vector representations.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] To use these for downstream applications, an additional head needs to be trained to interpret them.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] For example, to use it for classification, one can add a shallow MLP on top of it that outputs a probability distribution over classes.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The original paper uses a linear-GeLU-linear-softmax network.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The original ViT was an encoder-only Transformer supervise-trained to predict the image label from the patches of the image.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] As in the case of BERT, it uses a special token `<CLS>` in the input side, and the corresponding output vector is used as the only input of the final output MLP head.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The special token is an architectural hack to allow the model to compress all information relevant for predicting the image label into one vector.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Transformers found their initial applications in natural language processing tasks, as demonstrated by language models such as BERT and GPT-3.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] By contrast the typical image processing system uses a convolutional neural network (CNN).
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Well-known projects include Xception, ResNet, EfficientNet, DenseNet, and Inception.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Transformers measure the relationships between pairs of input tokens (words in the case of text strings), termed attention.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The cost is quadratic in the number of tokens.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] For images, the basic unit of analysis is the pixel.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] However, computing relationships for every pixel pair in a typical image is prohibitive in terms of memory and computation.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Instead, ViT computes relationships among pixels in various small sections of the image (e.g., 16x16 pixels), at a drastically reduced cost.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The sections (with positional embeddings) are placed in a sequence.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Each section is arranged into a linear sequence and multiplied by the embedding matrix.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The result, with the position embedding is fed to the transformer.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] After the ViT processes an image, it produces some embedding vectors.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] These must be converted to a single class probability prediction by some kind of network.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] In the original ViT and Masked Autoencoder, they used a dummy `[CLS]` token, in emulation of the BERT language model.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The output at `[CLS]` is the classification token, which is then processed by a LayerNorm-feedforward-softmax module into a probability distribution.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Later papers demonstrated that GAP and MAP both perform better than BERT-like pooling.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] A variant of MAP was proposed as **class attention**, which applies MAP, then feedforward, then MAP again.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The **Masked Autoencoder** took inspiration from denoising autoencoders and context encoders.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The first one ("encoder") takes in image patches with positional encoding, and outputs vectors representing each patch.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The second one (called "decoder", even though it is still an encoder-only Transformer) takes in vectors with positional encoding and outputs image patches again.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] During training, input images (224px x 224 px in the original implementation) are split along a designated number of lines on each axis, producing image patches.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] A certain percentage of patches are selected to be masked out by mask tokens, while all others are retained in the image.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The network is tasked with reconstructing the image from the remaining unmasked patches.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Mask tokens in the original implementation are learnable vector quantities.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] A linear projection with positional embeddings is then applied to the vector of unmasked patches.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Experiments varying mask ratio on networks trained on the ImageNet-1K dataset found 75% mask ratios achieved high performance on both finetuning and linear-probing of the encoder's latent space.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The MAE processes only unmasked patches during training, increasing the efficiency of data processing in the encoder and lowering the memory usage of the transformer.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] A less computationally-intensive ViT is used for the decoder in the original implementation of the MAE.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Masked patches are added back to the output of the encoder block as mask tokens and both are fed into the decoder.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] A reconstruction loss is computed for the masked patches to assess network performance.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] In prediction, the decoder architecture is discarded entirely.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The input image is split into patches by the same algorithm as in training, but no patches are masked out.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] A linear projection with a positional embedding is applied to each patch, and the resulting embedding vector representations of each patch are fed to the encoder.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Several derivatives of the original MAE have been explored.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The MAE has been applied for self-supervised pretraining in medical contexts, including for chest X-ray interpretation.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Derivatives of the MAE have been applied in this context to better serve as pretraining in medical contexts.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] set to create local attention maps for medical images in order to constrain which patches are masked out.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Medically Supervised MAE achieved state-of-the-art performance as of Jan.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] GCLM-MAE uses GCLM to extract texture information from images in order to preserve texture information.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] It addresses an issue in which a classic MAE oversmooths images, causing a loss of granular detail that may be important in medical contexts.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] GLCM-MAE achieves state-of-the-art performance on the identification of gallbladder cancer, breast cancer imaged from ultrasound, pneumonia imaged from X-rays, and COVID-19 imaged from computed tomography as of Jul.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] R-MAE replaces patch-generating step in the original MAE with an algorithm for assigning individual pixels to regions of interest in an image, which are masked out together.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The region encoding architecture is standalone, but can be combined with the MAE for region reconstruction.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] SiamMAE is a network designed to apply MAEs to video data.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Samples two frames from a video (compared to one in the original MAE), and labels them as "past" and "future." The network masks out a majority of the patches (~95%) in the future frame, leaves the past frame untouched, and passes both through the MAE encoder block.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The decoder architecture is replaced with attention blocks that map patches from the past frame to the future frame for reconstruction.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] SiamMAE achieves competitive performance against larger models on segmentation and propagation in videos.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] A similar architecture was BERT ViT (BEiT), published concurrently.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Like the Masked Autoencoder, the **DINO** (self-**di**stillation with **no** labels) method is a way to train a ViT by self-supervision.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] DINO is a form of teacher-student self-distillation.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] In DINO, the student is the model itself, and the teacher is an exponential average of the student's past states.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The method is similar to previous works like momentum contrast and bootstrap your own latent (BYOL).
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The loss function used in DINO is the cross-entropy loss between the output of the teacher network ( $f_{\theta '_{t}}$ ) and the output of the student network ( $f_{\theta _{t}}$ ).
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The teacher network is an exponentially decaying average of the student network's past parameters: $\theta '_{t}=\alpha \theta _{t}+\alpha (1-\alpha )\theta _{t-1}+\cdots$ .
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The inputs to the networks are two different crops of the same image, represented as $T(x)$ and $T'(x)$ , where x is the original image.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The loss function is written as $L(f_{\theta '_{t}}(T(x)),f_{\theta _{t}}(T'(x)))$ One issue is that the network can "collapse" by always outputting the same value ( y ), regardless of the input.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] In January 2024, Meta AI Research released an updated version called DINOv2 with improvements in architecture, loss function, and optimization technique.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] It was trained on a larger and more diverse dataset.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The features learned by DINOv2 were more transferable, meaning it had better performance in downstream tasks.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] In August 2025, Meta AI Research released DINOv3, an update to DINOv2.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] It introduced image-text alignment like CLIP.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] It scaled up the model to 7B parameters and the training dataset to 1.7B images (obtained by diversity-sampling an initial dataset with 17B images).
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Architecturally, it introduced two improvements: Gram anchoring and axial RoPE (Rotary Positional Embeddings) with jittering.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Gram anchoring applies teacher-student self-distillation for the Gram matrix between the feature vectors of the patches of an image.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] It avoids the previously observed problem of degradation of dense feature maps: While performance on global tasks (like classification) continued to improve, performance on dense tasks (like segmentation) would peak early and then decline, with feature maps becoming noisy.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Axial RoPE makes the model more robust to varying image resolutions, scales, and aspect ratios.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The **TimeSformer** was designed for video understanding tasks, and it applied a factorized self-attention, similar to the factorized convolution kernels found in the Inception CNN architecture.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Schematically, it divides a video into frames, and each frame into a square grid of patches (same as ViT).
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Let each patch coordinate be denoted by $x,y,t$ , denoting horizontal, vertical, and time.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The TimeSformer also considered other attention layer designs, such as the "height attention layer" where the requirement is $x'=x,t'=t$ .
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] However, they found empirically that the best design interleaves one space attention layer and one time attention layer.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] In **ViT-VQGAN**, there are two ViT encoders and a discriminator.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] One encodes 8x8 patches of an image into a list of vectors, one for each patch.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The vectors can only come from a discrete set of "codebook", as in vector quantization.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Another encodes the quantized vectors back to image patches.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The training objective attempts to make the reconstruction image (the output image) faithful to the input image.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The discriminator (usually a convolutional network, but other networks are allowed) attempts to decide if an image is an original real image, or a reconstructed image by the ViT.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The idea is essentially the same as vector quantized variational autoencoder (VQVAE) plus generative adversarial network (GAN).
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] After such a ViT-VQGAN is trained, it can be used to code an arbitrary image into a list of symbols, and code an arbitrary list of symbols into an image.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] The list of symbols can be used to train into a standard autoregressive transformer (like GPT), for autoregressively generating an image.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Further, one can take a list of caption-image pairs, convert the images into strings of symbols, and train a standard GPT-style transformer.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Then at test time, one can just give an image caption, and have it autoregressively generate the image.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Other examples include the visual transformer, CoAtNet, CvT, the data-efficient ViT (DeiT), etc.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] In the Transformer in Transformer architecture, each layer applies a vision Transformer layer on each image patch embedding, add back the resulting tokens to the embedding, then applies another vision Transformer layer.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Typically, ViT uses patch sizes larger than standard CNN kernels (3x3 to 7x7).
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] ViT is more sensitive to the choice of the optimizer, hyperparameters, and network depth.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] Preprocessing with a layer of smaller-size, overlapping (stride < size) convolutional filters helps with performance and stability.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] ViT have been used in many computer vision tasks with excellent results and in some cases even state-of-the-art, such as in image classification, object detection, video deepfake detection, image segmentation, anomaly detection, image synthesis, cluster analysis, autonomous driving.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] ViT had been used for image generation as backbones for GAN and for diffusion models (diffusion transformer, or DiT).
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] DINO has been demonstrated to learn useful representations for clustering images and exploring morphological profiles on biological datasets, such as images generated with the Cell Painting assay.
[src:segment-anything/vision-transformer] In 2024, a 113 billion-parameter ViT model was designed (the largest ViT to date) for weather and climate prediction, and trained on the Frontier supercomputer with a throughput of 1.6 exaFLOPs.
